ce:section.ce:para:
The size and thickness of the GQDs obtained in ethyleneglycol (EG) (Fig. 3
                        ), DMF (Fig. 4
                        ), and DMSO (Fig. 5
                        ) were characterised by atomic force microscopy (AFM). It can be seen that after the refluxing, GO was broken into small clusters of a few nanometers in size. From performed particle size distributions (insets in Figs. 3–5) can be seen that the lateral dimensions of dots are up to 20nm in DMF and DMSO and slightly bigger in EG (up to 40nm). Heights of the particles are mostly around 1nm (again slightly bigger in EG – up to 4nm), which is very close to reported value of one GO sheet thickness [37,38]; some discrepancy (i.e. heights of particles below 0.5nm) is caused by limitation of AFM and character of the measurement. Observed variation in cluster size could induce a shift in the emission wavelength of GQDs in different solvents.
